,"1172–1237":"1172–1237","1201–1237":"1201–1237","1135–1201":"1135–1201","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","Abt 1201":"circa 1201","before 1201":"vóór 1201","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","Abt 1165":"circa 1165","about 1216":"circa 1216","1165":"1165","about 1189":"circa 1189","1172":"1172","Marden, Wiltshire, England":"Marden, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","La Ferte-Mace, Normandy, France":"La Ferté-Macé, Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bridgwater, Somersetshire, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1165–1216":"about 1165–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1172–1237":"1172–1237","1201–1237":"1201–1237","1135–1201":"1135–1201","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","Abt 1201":"about 1201","before 1201":"before 1201","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","Abt 1165":"about 1165","about 1216":"about 1216","1165":"1165","about 1189":"about 1189","1172":"1172","Marden, Wiltshire, England":"Marden, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","La Ferte-Mace, Normandy, France":"La Ferté-Macé, Orne, Normandy, France","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bridgwater, Somersetshire, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Ferte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dino, Domenic, Domenico, Salvatore, Santo, Saverio.","Italian (<b>Berté</b>): probably from a short form of the personal name <i>Bertiere</i>, a derivative of   Berto  .","German: variant of   Bert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Berto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mario, Jose Cruz, Manuel, Virgilio.  Italian Dario, Mauro, Vito.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Berto</i>, a short form ofany of various ancient Germanic names formed with <i>bert</i> (from<i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’), for example <i>Alberto</i>,<i>Gilberto</i>, <i>Norberto</i>, <i>Roberto</i>, <i>Umberto</i>.","Hungarian (<b>Bertó</b>): from a pet form of the personalname <i>Bertalan</i>, Hungarian form of   Bartholomew  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de la Ferte was born about 1165, in La Ferté-Macé, Orne, Normandy, France, his father, Seigneur Mathieu de La Ferte-Mace, was 32 and his mother, Gundreda Paynel, was 31. He married Margaret De Briwere about 1189, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1216, in Marden, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"Abt 1165–1216":"umbes 1165–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1172–1237":"1172–1237","1201–1237":"1201–1237","1135–1201":"1135–1201","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","Abt 1201":"umbes 1201","before 1201":"enne 1201","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","about 1216":"umbes 1216","1165":"1165","about 1189":"umbes 1189","1172":"1172","Marden, Wiltshire, England":"Marden, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","La Ferte-Mace, Normandy, France":"La Ferté-Macé, Orne, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bridgwater, Somersetshire, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1165–1216":"noin 1165–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1172–1237":"1172–1237","1201–1237":"1201–1237","1135–1201":"1135–1201","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","Abt 1201":"noin 1201","before 1201":"ennen vuotta 1201","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","Abt 1165":"noin 1165","about 1216":"noin 1216","1165":"1165","about 1189":"noin 1189","1172":"1172","Marden, Wiltshire, England":"Marden, Wiltshire, England","England":"England","La Ferte-Mace, Normandy, France":"La Ferté-Macé, Orne, Normandie, Ranska","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Bridgwater, Somersetshire, England":"Bridgwater, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1165–1216":"environ 1165–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","1172–1237":"1172–1237","1201–1237":"1201–1237","1135–1201":"1135–1201","1135–1216":"1135–1216","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","Abt 1201":"environ 1201","before 1201":"avant 1201","1135":"1135","1201":"1201","Abt 1165":"environ 1165","about 1